messages.content: Por favor, inicia el servidor de desarrollo de la aplicación POStheme. El proyecto está ubicado en /home/lr/ecoDev/work/Proyectos/POStheme. Usa el comando npm run dev para iniciar el servidor en el puerto 5173.

I'll help you start the development server for the POStheme application. Let me run the npm run dev command to start the server on port 5173.

First, I'll check if the project directory exists and then start the development server:
Great! The project directory exists. Now I'll check if there's a package.json file and what scripts are available:
Perfect! The package.json file exists. Now let me check what scripts are available in the package.json to confirm the 'dev' script exists:
Perfect! I can see that the project is a React application using Vite as the build tool, and it has a "dev" script that runs "vite". Now I'll start the development server:
The development server has been started in the background. Let me check if the server is running and on which port:
It seems netstat is not installed on your system. Let me try using ss instead to check if the server is running:

Great! The development server is running on port 5173. I can see that the server is listening on localhost (IPv6 loopback address ::1) on port 5173.

Let me also check the actual output from the development server to confirm it started properly:

Perfect! I can confirm that the Vite development server is running. I can see the process with PID 2385735 that's running the Vite server from your POStheme project directory.

The development server for POStheme has been successfully started on port 5173. You can now access the application by opening your browser and navigating to http://localhost:5173 or http://127.0.0.1:5173.

The server is running in the background and will continue to serve the application until you stop it. The Vite development server provides features like hot module replacement (HMR) which will automatically update your browser when you make changes to the code.

To stop the server later, you would need to kill the process using the PID (2385735) or use a command like `kill 2385735`.
